04998nam a22005895i 9780226923994DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226923994  a(DE-B1597)524701  a(OCoLC)829713432  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ127.E85bG35 2014 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a509.032223  aTB 23552rvk1 aGal, Ofer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBaroque Science /cRaz Chen-Morris, Ofer Gal. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b51 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. Observation -- t1. Science’s Disappearing Observer: Baroque Optics and the Enlightenment of Vision -- t2. Per aenigmate: Mirrors and Lenses as Cognitive Tools in Medieval and Renaissance Europe -- t3. The Specter of the Telescope: Radical Instrumentalism from Galileo to Hooke -- tII. Mathematization -- t4. Nature’s Drawing: Problems and Resolutions in the Mathematization of Motion -- t5. From Divine Order to Human Approximation: Mathematics in Baroque Science -- t6. The Emergence of Baroque Mathematical Natural Philosophy: An Archeology of the Inverse Square Law -- tIII. Passions -- t7. Passions, Imagination, and the Persona of the New Savant -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Baroque Science, Ofer Gal and Raz Chen-Morris present a radically new perspective on the scientific revolution of the seventeenth century. Instead of celebrating the triumph of reason and rationality, they study the paradoxes and anxieties that stemmed from the New Science and the intellectual compromises that shaped it and enabled its spectacular success. Gal and Chen-Morris show how the protagonists of the new mathematical natural philosophy grasped at the very far and very small by entrusting observation to the mediation of artificial instruments, and how they justified this mediation by naturalizing and denigrating the human senses. They show how the physical-mathematical ordering of heavens and earth demanded obscure and spurious mathematical procedures, replacing the divine harmonies of the late Renaissance with an assemblage of isolated, contingent laws and approximated constants. Finally, they show how the new savants, forced to contend that reason is hopelessly estranged from its surrounding world and that nature is irreducibly complex, turned to the passions to provide an alternative, naturalized foundation for their epistemology and ethics. Enforcing order in the face of threatening chaos, blurring the boundaries of the natural and the artificial, and mobilizing the passions in the service of objective knowledge, the New Science, Gal and Chen-Morris reveal, is a Baroque phenomenon: deeply entrenched in and crucially formative of the culture of its time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDiscoveries in sciencexHistoryy17th century. 0aMathematicsxHistoryy17th century. 0aOpticsxHistoryy17th century. 0aSciencexHistoryy17th century. 0aSciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy17th century. 70(DE-601)1062193240(DE-588)4041421-8aNaturwissenschaften2gnd 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ascientific revolution, science, scientist, 17th century, 1600s, reason, rationality, paradox, anxiety, theory, compromise, intellectual, mathematical, natural world, philosophy, philosophical, mediation, physics, mathematics, interdisciplinary, renaissance, laws, legal issues, litigation, epistemology, ethics, discovery, medieval, galileo, hooke, divine.1 aChen-Morris, Raz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/